DEFINITIONS -

Integers - 
A whole number; a number that is not a fraction or decimal

Floats - 
They represent real numbers and are written with a decimal point

Bool/Boolean -
One of Python's built-in data types. It's used to represent the truth value of an expression; True or False

String -
Is a sequence of characters. It is a derived data type. Strings are immutable. This means that once defined, they cannot be changed. !!!! = ""

*********************
Variable example : 

a = 16

b = 17

print(a)
print(b)
print(a + b)
print(b - a)

type(a) = should use this command in shell and get a response of <class 'int'>
type(b) = should use this command in shell and get a response of <class 'int'>

**********************

String example + print("___") function :


print("Hello World")

print("How are you doing?)

comment = "I'm good, thank you"

type(comment) = should use this command in shell and get a response of <class 'str'>

**********************
Floats and Boolean Examples :

a = 1.0

b = True

type(b) = should use this command in shell and get a response of <class 'float'>. Check the definition!
type(a) = should use this command in shell and get a response of <class 'bool'>. Check the definition!
